<tr>
<td>
<p style="text-align: center;">STAR E-182</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">American Dreams from <i>Scarface</i> to <i>Easy Rider</i></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Fall Term 2017</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">SYLLABUS</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Prof. Eric Rentschler<span><span class="Apple-tab-span"> </span>                                                                        </span><span>Lectures online</span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Barker Center 350<span><span class="Apple-tab-span"> </span>                                                                            </span>Written Online Discussions</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">        Please direct all course-related inquiries to Course Head TA, Charlotte Szilagyi, Ph.D.<br>        (szilagyi@fas.harvard.edu)</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Course Description:</strong></p>
<p>Is the so-called American dream dead? The notion once essentialized the grand promise of a better, fuller, and richer life. At the present moment, however, it seems to have lost its evocative persuasiveness as a collective myth. In a time of cultural crisis and political emergency, this Harvard Extension School course has a pressing mission. It aims to further a dynamic understanding of American dreams, to understand their complexities and contradictions, to appreciate their many different manifestations and historical shapes, and above all to take measure of their relevance and function in the world we inhabit.</p>
<p>In this endeavor we will study the various ways in which Hollywood’s fantasy machinery has created designs for living, indeed the most influential and resonant incarnations of American dreams. We will analyze popular films produced during crucial junctures in the modern history of the United States, from the Great Depression and World War II through the Cold War, McCarthy era, and the 1960s. We will consider the wide range of functions that commercial studio productions have assumed, how they at times have legitimated and sustained the status quo, but at others also have interrogated, exposed, and even indicted social inequity. The class offers a representative sampling of classical Hollywood features from 1932 to 1969, including <em>Scarface</em>, <em>It Happened One Night</em>, <em>The Wizard of Oz</em>, <em>Gone with the Wind, Citizen Kane, Casablanca, The Best Years of Our Lives, Detour, High Noon, The Invasion of the Body Snatchers, A Face in the Crowd,</em> <em>The Manchurian Candidate</em>, and <em>Easy Rider</em>.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Course Trailers:</strong> </p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a id="media_comment_m-3sJqnN1jYLSrWogKGufFtFcx2w9o8FpN" class="instructure_inline_media_comment video_comment" href="/media_objects/m-3sJqnN1jYLSrWogKGufFtFcx2w9o8FpN"></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a id="media_comment_m-3NehrM7TmzGNcVptr5JqKpdLT5MLJ6K3" class="instructure_inline_media_comment video_comment" href="/media_objects/m-3NehrM7TmzGNcVptr5JqKpdLT5MLJ6K3"></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"> </p>
<p><strong>Required Course Texts:</strong></p>
<p>Jim Cullen. <i>The American Dream: A Short History of an Idea That Shaped a Nation</i>. <br>Morris Dickstein. <i>Dancing in the Dark: A Cultural History of the Great Depression</i>. <br>Laura Mulvey. <i>Citizen Kane</i>.<br>Salman Rushdie. <i>The Wizard of Oz</i>.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Recommended:</strong></p>
<p>J. Hoberman. <i>An Army of Phantoms. American Movies and the Making of the Cold War</i>.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Required Articles:</strong></p>
<p>Readings marked as PDF (i.e. articles) can be downloaded free, directly from the course website.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Course Requirements:</strong></p>
<p>Weekly postings (ca. 250 words) + responses<span><span class="Apple-tab-span"> </span>      </span><span>40% (400 points)</span></p>
<p>Midterm examination<span><span class="Apple-tab-span"> </span>                                             </span><span>20% (200 points)</span></p>
<p>Comprehensive final project<span><span class="Apple-tab-span"> </span>                                  </span><span>40% (400 points)</span></p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Academic Integrity</strong></p>
<p>Discussion and the exchange of ideas are essential to academic work. Any written work that you submit, including weekly responses, must be the result of your own research and writing and reflect your own approach to the topic. You must also adhere to standard citation practices in this discipline and properly cite any books, articles, websites, lectures, etc. that have helped you with your work. If you receive any help with your writing (feedback on drafts, etc.), you must also acknowledge this assistance.</p>
<p>You are responsible for understanding Harvard Extension School policies on academic integrity (<a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity%22%20%5Ct%20%22_blank"><span>www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity</span></a>) and how to use sources responsibly. Not knowing the rules, misunderstanding the rules, running out of time, submitting the wrong draft, or being overwhelmed with multiple demands are not acceptable excuses. There are no excuses for failure to uphold academic integrity. To support your learning about academic citation rules, please visit the Harvard Extension School Tips to Avoid Plagiarism (<a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism%22%20%5Ct%20%22_blank"><span>www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism</span></a>), where you'll find links to the Harvard Guide to Using Sources and two free online 15-minute tutorials to test your knowledge of academic citation policy. The tutorials are anonymous open-learning tools.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Disability Services</strong></p>
<p>The Extension School is committed to providing an accessible academic community. The Accessibility Oﬃce oﬀers a variety of accommodations and services to students with documented disabilities. Please visit <a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/disability-services-accessibility"> <span>www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/disability-services-accessibility</span><span> </span></a>for more information.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Course Schedule</strong></p>
<p>Lecture dates indicate when the recorded lectures will be taped; they are uploaded to the course website within 24 hours of the taping (and often on the same day). Outlines of each lecture will be posted each week on the course website as well as various handouts that elaborate and supplement class materials.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Course Films</strong></p>
<p>Because copyright agreements stipulate that the rightholders to films must receive payment, films will have to be accessed from a commercial source. All of the films we will be studying are available on amazon.com. Some of the films, to be sure, can be found on YouTube and other internet sites.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Course Schedule</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Part I. The Great Depression and the Second World War</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week I</p>
<p>Lecture 1: <strong>Introduction: “A Better, Richer, and Happier Life”</strong> 8/30 (repeated on 9/6)</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week II</p>
<p>Lecture 1: <strong>Introduction: “A Better, Richer, and Happier Life” (repeat)</strong> 9/6</p>
<p>Film: <em>Scarface</em> (1932, 93’)</p>
<p>Readings: Robert Warshow, “The Gangster as Tragic Hero”; David E. Ruth, “Criminal Businessmen”; <em>The American Dream</em> ("Introduction"--p.3-10)</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week III</p>
<p>Lecture 2: <strong>The Gangster as American Dreamer</strong> 9/11</p>
<p>Films: <em>It Happened One Night</em> (1934, 105’) and <em>King Kong</em> (1933 version) </p>
<p>Lecture 3: <strong>Show Business and National Renewal</strong> 9/13</p>
<p>Readings: <em>The American Dream</em> (Chapters 1&amp;2--p.11-58); Morris Dickstein, <em>Dancing in the Dark</em> (Chapter 7--p. 215-311)</p>
<p>  </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week IV</p>
<p>Lecture 4: <strong>The Great Ape and the Great Depression </strong>9/18</p>
<p>Film: <em>The Wizard of Oz</em> (1939, 101’) </p>
<p>Lecture 5: <strong>A Film Fantasy and Its Surplus Value</strong> 9/20</p>
<p>Readings: Lawrence W. Levine, “American Culture and the Great Depression” (PDF); Salman Rushdie, <em>The Wizard of Oz</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week V</p>
<p>Lecture 6: <strong>No Place Like Home</strong> 9/25</p>
<p>Film: <em>Gone with the Wind</em> (1939, 238’) </p>
<p>Lecture 7: <strong>Tara Incognita</strong> 9/27</p>
<p>Readings: Melvin B. Tolson, “<em>Gone with the Wind </em>Is More Dangerous Than <em>Birth of a Nation</em>”; J. E. Smyth, “Jezebels and Rebels, Cavaliers and Compromise, 1930-1939” (both PDF); <em>The American Dream</em> (59-131)</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week VI</p>
<p>Lecture 8: <strong>Beautiful Dreamers</strong> 10/2</p>
<p>Film: <em>The Grapes of Wrath</em> (1940, 129’) </p>
<p>Lecture 9: <strong>“We’ll Go On Forever, Cos We’re the People”</strong> 10/4</p>
<p>Readings: Leslie Gossage, “The Artful Propaganda of Ford’s <em>The Grapes of Wrath</em>” (PDF); Jason Arthur, “Where Is the Dust?” (both PDF) ; Morris Dickstein, <em>Dancing in the Dark</em> (477-495)</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week VII</p>
<p>October 9: Columbus Day holiday</p>
<p>Film: <em>Citizen Kane</em> (Orson Welles, 1941, 119’) </p>
<p>Lecture 10: <strong>Pieces of a Puzzle</strong> 10/11</p>
<p>Readings: Morris Dickstein, <em>Dancing in the Dark</em> (342-354); Laura Mulvey, <em>Citizen Kane</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week VIII</p>
<p>Lecture 11: <strong>Made Men</strong> 10/16</p>
<p>Film: <em>Casablanca</em> (1942, 102’) </p>
<p>Lecture 12: <strong>The Longing to Be Lonely</strong> 10/18</p>
<p>Readings: Umberto Eco, “<em>Casablanca</em>: Cult Movies and Intertextual Collage”; Barbara Deming, “The Reluctant War Hero” (both PDF)</p>
<p> </p>
<p>***Comprehensive Take-Home Midterm Examination*** 10/21-22</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Part II. Postwar Fallout</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week IX</p>
<p>Film: <em>The Best Years of Our Lives</em> (1946, 172’) </p>
<p>Lecture 13: <strong>Home Strange Home</strong> 10/25</p>
<p>Readings: Michael C. Adams, “A New World”; Robert Warshow, “The Anatomy of Falsehood” (both PDF); <em>The American Dream</em> (133-157)</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week X</p>
<p>Lecture 14: <strong>History That Hurts</strong> 10/30</p>
<p>Film: <em>Detour </em>(1945, 67’) and <em>High Noon</em> (1952, 85’)</p>
<p>Lecture 15: <strong>The Dark Side</strong> 11/1</p>
<p>Readings: Siegfried Kracauer, “Hollywood’s Terror Films”; Paul Schrader, “Notes on Film Noir”; Robert Warshow, “The Westerner”; Doug Williams, “Pilgrims and the Promised Land” (all PDF)</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week XI</p>
<p>Lecture 16: <strong>Revisionist Triggernometry</strong> 11/6</p>
<p>Film: <em>Invasion of the Body Snatchers</em> (1956, 80’) </p>
<p>Lecture 17: <strong>Pod Almighty</strong> 11/8</p>
<p>Readings: David Riesman, from <em>The Lonely Crowd</em>; Susan Sontag, “The Imagination of Disaster” (both PDF); <em>The American Dream</em> (159-190)</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week XII</p>
<p>Lecture 18: <strong>American Nightmares</strong> 11/13</p>
<p>Film: <em>A Face in the Crowd</em> (1957, 126’)</p>
<p>Lecture 19: <strong>“We Get Wise to ‘Em”</strong> 11/15</p>
<p>Readings: Vance Packard, “Politics and the Image Builders”; Norman Mailer, “The White Negro” (both PDF)</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week XIII</p>
<p><strong>Selected Short Films on the American Dream</strong> 11/20</p>
<p>Film: <em>The Manchurian Candidate</em> (1962, 126’)</p>
<p>Readings: Richard Hofstadter, “The Paranoid Style in American Politics”; Michael Rogin, “Communism, Motherhood, and Cold War Movies” (both PDF)</p>
<p>Thanksgiving holiday</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Week XIV</p>
<p>Lecture 20: <strong>Hell</strong> 11/27</p>
<p>Film: <em>Easy Rider</em> (1969, 95’) </p>
<p>Lecture 21: <strong>“We Blew It”</strong> 11/30</p>
<p>Reading: Lyndon B. Johnson, “Great Society Speech”</p>
<p>http://www.h-net.org/~hst306/documents/great.html</p>
<p> </p>
<p>***Comprehensive Final Project due 10 a.m. Tue, Dec 12***</p>
<p> </p>
<p>           </p>
<p> </p>
</td>
</tr>
